        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=The sexual and reproductive health and rights of young people with intellectual disability: a scoping review; citation_author=Carter, A; citation_author=Strnadová, I; citation_author=Watfern, C; citation_author=Pebdani, R; citation_author=Bateson, D; citation_author=Loblinzk, J; citation_author=Guy, R; citation_author=Newman, C; citation_publication_date=in press; citation_journal_title=Sexuality Research and Social Policy">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Anticipatory grief of spousal and adult children caregivers of people with dementia; citation_author=Cheung, D; citation_author=Ho, K; citation_author=Cheung, TF; citation_author=Lam, S; citation_author=Tse, M; citation_publication_date=2018; citation_journal_title=BMC Palliative Care; citation_volume=17; citation_firstpage=124; citation_doi=10.1186/s12904-018-0376-3">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Voices from Australia – concerns about HIV associated neurocognitive disorder; citation_author=Cummins, D; citation_author=Waters, D; citation_author=Aggar, C; citation_author=Crawford, D; citation_author=Fethney, J; citation_author=O&#39;Connor, C; citation_publication_date=2018; citation_journal_title=AIDS Care; citation_volume=30; citation_firstpage=609; citation_lastpage=617; citation_doi=10.1080/09540121.2018.1426826">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Queer(y)ing dementia – bringing queer theory and studies of dementia into dialogue; citation_author=King, A; citation_author=Westwood, S; citation_author=Price, E; citation_publication_date=2016; citation_inbook=Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Trans* Individuals Living with Dementia. Concepts, Practice and Rights; citation_firstpage=51; citation_lastpage=64">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Working with lesbian and gay people with dementia; citation_author=Mackenzie, J; citation_publication_date=2009; citation_journal_title=Journal of Dementia Care; citation_volume=17; citation_firstpage=17; citation_lastpage=19">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=How do lesbian and gay people experience dementia?; citation_author=McParland, J; citation_author=Camic, PM; citation_publication_date=2018; citation_journal_title=Dementia; citation_volume=17; citation_firstpage=452; citation_lastpage=477; citation_doi=10.1177/1471301216648471">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Champions’ perspectives on implementing the National Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Intersex Ageing and Aged Care Strategy in Queensland; citation_author=McPhail, R; citation_author=Fulop, L; citation_publication_date=2016; citation_journal_title=Australian Health Review; citation_volume=40; citation_firstpage=633; citation_lastpage=640; citation_doi=10.1071/AH15185">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses: the PRISMA Statement; citation_author=Moher, D; citation_author=Liberati, A; citation_author=Tetzlaff, J; citation_author=Altman, DG; citation_publication_date=2009; citation_journal_title=Journal of Clinical Epidemiology; citation_volume=62; citation_firstpage=1006; citation_lastpage=1012; citation_doi=10.1016/j.jclinepi.2009.06.005">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Lesbian and gay elders: connecting care providers through a telephone support group; citation_author=Moore, WR; citation_publication_date=2002; citation_journal_title=Journal of Gay and Lesbian Social Services; citation_volume=14; citation_firstpage=23; citation_lastpage=41; citation_doi=10.1300/J041v14n03_02">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Meeting the needs of LGBT people affected by dementia: the story of the LGBT dementia support group; citation_author=Newman, R; citation_author=Price, E; citation_author=Ward, R; citation_author=Rivers, I; citation_author=Sutherland, M; citation_publication_date=2012; citation_inbook=Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Ageing: Biographical Approaches for Inclusive Care and Support; citation_firstpage=183; citation_lastpage=195">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=Coming out to care: gay and lesbian carers’ experiences of dementia services; citation_author=Price, E; citation_publication_date=2010; citation_journal_title=Health and Social Care in the Community; citation_volume=18; citation_firstpage=160; citation_lastpage=168; citation_doi=10.1111/j.1365-2524.2009.00884.x">
        <meta name="citation_reference"  content="citation_title=What happens when we forget our own narrative: transgender dementia case study; citation_author=Scharaga, EA; citation_author=Chang, A; citation_author=Kulas, JF; citation_publication_date=2021; citation_journal_title=Clinical Neuropsychologist; citation_volume=35">
        <meta name="citation_abstract"  content="Dementia, a global health priority, poses a disproportionately high risk to lesbian, gay, bisexual and trans plus (LGBT+)/gender and sexuality diverse people. Despite this, little research has explored the lived experience of LGBT+ people with dementia or their care partners. This scoping review aims to understand what the literature reveals about their experiences, the ways in which their lives have been investigated, to inform future research, policy and practice. Using an established scoping review methodology, we identified seven papers that reported empirical research on the lived experience of LGBT+ people with dementia and their care partners. Only a single study reported on in two of the papers included people who were trans. This in itself reveals how rarely LGBT+ people are asked to speak about how dementia has shaped their lives in academic research. Our reflexive thematic analysis indicates that LGBT+ people with dementia and their care partners endure overlapping forms of disadvantage. This results in heightened experiences of fear and discrimination, lack of services and compounded social isolation. Importantly, while dementia was embodied as interference and loss by LGBT+ people, it was their gender and sexuality differences that provided solace, even in the face of disadvantage. Importantly, people&#39;s relationships with LGBT+ identities were framed as fundamental for safety, resilience and wellbeing, rather than a complicating or confounding factor in living with dementia.">
        <meta name="citation_doi"  content="10.1017/S0144686X22000538">
    
